Project: Data-driven Insights using Python: FoodHub Data Analysis

Problem Statement

Context

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. An online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub, offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app. The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirm the pick-up in the app and travel to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in its online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand for different restaurants, which will help them enhance their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company, and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company improve its business.

Data Description

The data contains different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

# Calculate percentages before rounding
percentages_before = (value_counts / len(food_order_data)) * 100

# After rounding
rounded_ratings = food_order_data['rating'].round(0)
rounded_value_counts = rounded_ratings.value_counts()
percentages_after = (rounded_value_counts / len(food_order_data)) * 100

# Focus on integer ratings (adjust to floats [3.0, 4.0, 5.0] if needed)
for_rating = [3.0, 4.0, 5.0] if any(isinstance(i, float) for i in percentages_before.index) else [3, 4, 5]
percentages_before = percentages_before[percentages_before.index.isin(for_rating)]
percentages_after = percentages_after[percentages_after.index.isin(for_rating)]

# Calculate change
percent_change = (percentages_after - percentages_before).round(0).astype(int)

# Add plus sign for positive, percent for all
percent_change_str = percent_change.astype(str)
percent_change_str = percent_change_str.mask(percent_change > 0, '+' + percent_change_str)
percent_change_str = percent_change_str + '%'

print("Change in percent for ratings 3, 4, 5 (after - before rounding):")
print(percent_change_str)

col = "cost_of_the_order"
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))

# Histogram
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
sns.histplot(data=food_order_data, x=col, bins=20, kde=True)
mean_val = food_order_data[col].mean()
median_val = food_order_data[col].median()
plt.axvline(mean_val, color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'Mean: {mean_val:.2f}')
plt.axvline(median_val, color='g', linestyle='-', label=f'Median: {median_val:.2f}')
plt.legend()
plt.title(f"Histogram of {col}")

# Boxplot
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
sns.boxplot(data=food_order_data, x=col)
Q1 = food_order_data[col].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = food_order_data[col].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1
ypos = 0.5
x_min, x_max = food_order_data[col].min(), food_order_data[col].max()
plt.text(x_min + (x_max - x_min)*0.15, ypos, f'Q1: {Q1:.2f}', ha='center', color='black')
plt.text(x_min + (x_max - x_min)*0.40, ypos, f'Median: {median_val:.2f}', ha='center', color='black')
plt.text(x_min + (x_max - x_min)*0.65, ypos, f'Q3: {Q3:.2f}', ha='center', color='black')
plt.text(x_min + (x_max - x_min)*0.90, ypos, f'IQR: {IQR:.2f}', ha='center', color='black')
plt.title(f"Boxplot of {col}")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
  • This histogram of order cost shows which price ranges are most popular among customers. Most customers place orders in the $14 range, so adding more options at this price point could increase sales, ie Five Below
  • This box plot shows most orders are 1222,withatypicalorderat1222,withatypicalorderat14, but a few much higher-cost orders, suggesting potential for coupons of the higher priced items to increase sales.

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]

In [211]:
# Write the code here
# Initialize commission as 0
food_order_data["commission"] = 0.0

food_order_data.loc[
    food_order_data["cost_of_the_order"] > 20, #creates a boolean mask selecting all rows where the order cost is greater than 20
     "commission" #column being updated
    ] = 0.25 * food_order_data["cost_of_the_order"] #multiply by 25%


food_order_data.loc[
    (food_order_data["cost_of_the_order"] > 5) & (food_order_data["cost_of_the_order"] <= 20), #creates a boolean mask selecting all rows where the order cost is greater than 5 and less than or equal to 20
    "commission" #column being updated
    ] = 0.15 * food_order_data["cost_of_the_order"] #multiply by 15%

net_revenue = food_order_data["commission"].sum() #add the two net revenues
print("Net revenue generated by the company: $", round(net_revenue,2))

Net revenue generated by the company: $ 6166.3

Observations:

These results show the company generated $6,166.30 in net revenue from commissions on food orders, using different rates for high- and mid-value sales. Business suggestions include monitoring how commission structures affect profits and restaurant partnerships, and optimizing pricing to balance company revenue with competitive restaurant offerings.

Question 15: The company wants to analyze the total time required to deliver the food. What percentage of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed? (The food has to be prepared and then delivered.) [2 marks]

In [212]:
# Write the code here
# Total time from order placed to delivered
food_order_data["total_time"] = food_order_data["food_preparation_time"] + food_order_data["delivery_time"]

#Count valid rows (both times present)
valid_orders = food_order_data["total_time"].notna().sum()

# Orders taking more than 60 minutes
orders_over_60 = (food_order_data["total_time"] > 60).sum()

# Percentage of such orders
percent_over_60 = (orders_over_60 / valid_orders) * 100

print("Percentage of orders taking more than 60 minutes:", round(percent_over_60,1),"%")

Percentage of orders taking more than 60 minutes: 10.5 %

Observations:

These results show that 10.5% of orders take longer than 60 minutes from placement to delivery. Business suggestions include setting better delivery time expectations and offering perks (like discounts or loyalty points) to keep customers happy when delays happen.

Conclusion and Business Recommendations

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]

Conclusions

  • American and Japanese cuisine are the most popular on weekends, while order delivery times are faster on weekends compared to weekdays.
  • A small percentage (10.5%) of orders take more than 60 minutes, but most customers receive their food in a reasonable time.
  • Restaurants with high rating counts and average ratings above 4 are well-positioned for positive promotions.

Business Recommendations

  • Advertise and offer promotions for the most popular and highly-rated cuisines, especially American and Japanese, to attract new customers and retain loyal ones.
  • To support staff and improve weekday delivery times, consider hiring part-time or on-call employees during peak hours so that regular staff are not overstretched.
  • Celebrate employee achievements during busy periods and ensure transparent communication with customers by setting realistic delivery expectations and providing perks for longer waits.
  • Use customer feedback and order patterns to guide menu updates, delivery strategies, and targeted loyalty rewards.
